 false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.995122492313385, "span": {"begin": 1141, "end": 1153}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5241"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "nuclear progesterone receptor", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9918832778930664, "span": {"begin": 1174, "end": 1203}}, {"id": ["mesh:D011374"], "is_neural_normalized": false, "mention": "progesterone", "obj": "drug", "prob": 0.9575844407081604, "span": {"begin": 1182, "end": 1194}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:190"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "nuclear receptor transcription factor superfamily", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9879948496818542, "span": {"begin": 1230, "end": 1279}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1327, "end": 1329}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:5351"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "LH", "obj": "gene", "prob": null, "span": {"begin": 1382, "end": 1384}}, {"id": ["NCBIGene:6046"], "is_neural_normalized": true, "mention": "FSH", "obj": "gene", "prob": 0.9738502502441406, "span": {"begin": 1389, "end": 1392}}], "text": "Some sections of the KE description were adapted from AOPs 309.  Luteinizing hormone (LH), together with follicle-stimulating hormone (FSH,) is one of the glycoprotein hormones, called gonadotropins, that control gonadal functions interacting trough specific receptors.&nbsp; LH and FSH are secreted from the anterior pituitary gland in response to GnRH and play a complementary role in follicle development and ovulation. In many species, LH receptor (LHR) is primarily expressed in reproductive organs and functions coordinately to control steroidogenesis and ovulation. LHR is expressed primarily in the theca and granulosa cells of preovulatory ovarian follicles. In ovarian theca cells, LH through interaction with LHR, stimulates the secretion of androgens that are transferred to granulosa cells to be converted to oestradiol (E2) by aromatase. In granulosa cells, FSH stimulates the development of ovarian follicles, while LH action is involved in follicle development and maturation. LH regulates the expression of a variety of genes essential for ovulation which convert from cholesterol to pregnenolone resulting the synthesis of progesterone.&nbsp; In fish, the nuclear progesterone receptor, which is a member of the nuclear receptor transcription factor superfamily, has been suggested as an essential factor for LH-dependent ovulation. In conclusion, A deficiency in LH and FSH production or action (e.g., receptor activation) compromises gametogenesis and gonadal steroid production thereby reducing female fertility.", "timestamp": "Fri May 15 21:35:26 +0000 2026"}